<title>KOrganizer workshop: Exchange Plugin</title>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-overview">
<title>Overview</title>

<para>
The &korganizer; Exchange plugin allows you to access your calendar on an
Microsoft Exchange&reg; server from &korganizer;. You can import the
appointments in a certain date range into your &korganizer; calendar,
you can export appointments (one at a time) from your &korganizer; calendar
to the Exchange server&reg; and you can delete appointments (also one at
a time) from the Exchange server&reg;. The plugin uses the WebDAV protocol
to access the Exchange server&reg;.
</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-requirements">
<title>Requirements</title>

<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>&korganizer; version 3.1 beta2 or later</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Microsoft Exchange Server 2000&reg;</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>On the Exchange Server&reg;, Outlook Web Access needs to be enabled,
since this also enables the WebDAV protocol</para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-enabling">
<title>Enabling the Exchange Plugin</title>

<para>
The Exchange Plugin is disabled by default, so you need to enable
the plugin by accessing <menuchoice><guimenu>Settings</guimenu>
<guimenuitem>Configure Plugins</guimenuitem></menuchoice>
from &korganizer;. You should see this dialog appear:
</para>

<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="ep_enable.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><para>Enabling the Exchange Plugin</para></textobject>
</mediaobject>

<para>
In this dialog, enable the <guilabel>Microsoft Exchange 2000 plugin
for &korganizer;</guilabel> and click <guibutton>OK</guibutton>. This
should enable a new <guimenu>Exchange</guimenu> menu in &korganizer;,
as in the following screenshot:
</para>

<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="ep_menu.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><para>Exchange menu</para></textobject>
</mediaobject>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-configuration">
<title>Configuration</title>

<para>
After the plugin is enabled, you should configure it. Choose
<guimenuitem>Configure...</guimenuitem> from the
<guimenu>Exchange</guimenu> menu. You should see this dialog appear:
</para>

<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="ep_config.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><para>Configuration</para></textobject>
</mediaobject>

<para>
In this dialog, you need to fill in:
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>the address of your Exchange server&reg;, &eg;
  <userinput>mail.mycompany.com</userinput></para></listitem>
<listitem><para>your account, or Exchange Mailbox, &eg;
  <userinput>joe</userinput>. Do not put in your domain
  here!</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>your password. If you fill in your
  password here, it is stored in encrypted format in
  <filename>~/.kde/share/config/korganizerrc</filename></para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>
</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-downloading">
<title>Downloading Appointments</title>

<para>
When you have configured the plugin, you can download events from your
account on the Exchange server&reg; into &korganizer;. Choose
<guimenuitem>Download...</guimenuitem> from the <guimenu>Exchange</guimenu>
menu. Now the following dialog will pop up:
</para>

<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="ep_download.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><para>Downloading Appointments</para></textobject>
</mediaobject>

<para>
In this dialog you need to fill in the date range you want to download
from the server. It defaults to the date range currently shown in
&korganizer;'s main window. When you click <guibutton>OK</guibutton>,
a progress dialog pops up:
</para>

<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="ep_progress.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><para>Progress Dialog</para></textobject>
</mediaobject>

<para>
The progress shown in this dialog does not correspond to the number of
appointments downloaded, but to the total number of accesses to the
Exchange server.
</para>

<para>
When download is finished, the downloaded appointments will show up in
the &korganizer; main window.
</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-uploading">
<title>Uploading Appointments</title>

<para>
You can upload appointments one at a time. First select an appointment
in &korganizer; by clicking on it. Then choose <guimenuitem>Upload
Event</guimenuitem> from the <guimenu>Exchange</guimenu> menu. A warning
message pops up, which is only important if you overwrite an existing
appointment on the Exchange server&reg; with an edited version of
the same appointment. If you click <guibutton>OK</guibutton>, your
appointment will be uploaded to the Exchange server&reg;.
</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-deleting">
<title>Deleting Appointments</title>

<para>
You can delete appointments also one at a time. First select
an appointment in &korganizer; by clicking on it. Then
choose <guimenuitem>Delete Event</guimenuitem> from the
<guimenu>Exchange</guimenu> menu. This also shows a warning message:
<computeroutput>Deleting a single appointment from a list of recurrent
appointments will delete all recurrences of the appointments</computeroutput>.
If you are OK with this, the appointment is deleted from the server
and from the &korganizer; calendar.
</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="exchange-plugin-debugging">
<title>Debugging</title>

<para>
If you find problems with the Exchange Plugin, please report them to the
<ulink url="mailto:kde-pim@mail.kde.org">kde-pim mailing list</ulink> or
to the KDE bug repository at <email>bugs.kde.org</email>.
</para>

<para>
Please include a full debug log from ~/.xsession-errors or from the
console from which you started X.
</para>

<para>
If you have compiled &korganizer; from source, please recompile will
full debug enabled:
<literallayout>
~$ cd src/kdepim
~/src/kdepim$ ./configure --enable-debug=full
~/src/kdepim$ cd libkpimexchange
~/src/kdepim/libkpimexchange$ make clean
~/src/kdepim/libkpimexchange$ make install
~/src/kdepim/libkpimexchange$ cd ../korganizer/plugins/exchange
~/src/kdepim/korganizer/plugins/exchange$ make clean
~/src/kdepim/korganizer/plugins/exchange$ make install
</literallayout>
</para>

<para>
You should see lines like
<literallayout>
korganizer: Registering Exchange Plugin...
korganizer: Creating Exchange Plugin...
korganizer: Creating ExchangeClient...
</literallayout>
in the log file.
</para>

<para>
Your help in improving the Exchange plugin is greatly appreciated.
</para>

</sect1>

